<td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p>I just wanted to say that is excellent advice for those of us just getting used to the strengths and weaknesses of the paladin.  I have found that when I'm in groups that when pulling more than 1 target, that if I can keep the other couple off the main tank, then the combat goes much smoother.  I take the damage and stun and root, and healing myself when need be till tank takes out main target.  A tank with multiple mobs on them runs the risk of getting stunned constantly and bashed around quickly, making the healer dump massive mana to keep the tank up in hit points.  Now yes I take a beating agrroing the other mobs, but its worth it in the long run.   <br />Another thing I do is cast a lot of strength buffs on the main hitters in the groups, and I cannot stress enough, buff the pets also, those extra hits with strength buffs help tremendously, a group of 6 with a couple of pet classes makes an effective group of 8, which is very nice in large mobs. <br />Now with a cleric (one that knows the finer sides of healer), you can ease up on the assist of healer and deal damage in close, with dual attacks and such.  Every little point helps.  I have also found that it seems the paladins roll becomes a lot clearer in mid and later levels. <br />I also make it a habit of knowing the paladins in the zone, and those that are lower level than I, I will help out a lot.  Besides isn't that what a paladin is for, to vanquish evil and help the weaker?  (This is just my opinion, no harm meant)</p>
